name: rushi
text:
starting multichain has never worked for any team ever.

ecosystem teams and founders have very limited bandwidth - venture, marketing, and even time.

we're more than happy to work with anyone and everyone and will never ever do signed exclusivities (never works).

for a young startup that has a bright idea, you should find a home chain and go all in on it for atleast 3-6 months - bullpost the chain, compete against other products on other chains, and live in the ecosystem.

there are too many "multichain liquidity aggregators" or "multichain consumer apps" that go pretty much nowhere. its very clear that the market does not need a multichain consumer app before there is a single consumer app - so its seen as larp.

some tips:

1) find a chain that aligns with your values, can provide you the financial support you need to grow your team (not exclusive grant money), and will let you build pmf.

2) do not play ecosystems with each other. i cant tell you the number of times ive texted other eco foudners about a team trying to play us for grant money or marketing. usually one of us or both will back out if we find out - founders talk, dont ruin ur rep.

3) embrace the branding. say the slogans, use the colors, do the amas. its free branding and acecss to the community - pretty much have thousands of people at ur disposal to test ur product on. get realtime feedback.

4) once you reach aave or uniswap level, then the multichain playbook makes sense as the app has enough PMF to serve multiple chains. 

being multichain before pmf has never worked for a team ever and will never work.

believe in something and go all in.

ty for the kind words @0xMai

quotedStatus.name: Mai üíæ
quotedStatus.text:
I have been building in crypto for 4 years, here is what I have learned about building Multichain:

As Curvance creeps up towards launch, and we start our radical transparency campaign, I think it makes sense to start writing more on X about the lessons we have learned, the opinions we have, and the opportunities we see.

I want to start off talking about building multichain and why you likely should not do it.

This will be primarily directed towards other application developers who are considering where to deploy or those curious about what it currently feels like to build in DeFi and the decisions that need to be made.

To state the obvious, it is quite weird that I recommend AGAINST building on multiple chains at once when we are doing just that. Over the last 2.5 years 6 months or more of development time has been spent specifically not having things blow up by connecting multiple chains.
 
Building meaningful relationships with ecosystem partners is more difficult as supporting applications on every chain integration multiplies the work necessary to hit critical mass very quickly (as it increases the work of development, marketing, and business development). This is thinking from the perspective of adding value to every ecosystem you touch versus being "multi-grant" that we saw last cycle of applications hoping from chain to chain trying to vacuum up incentives, which really is only value extractive, and not sustainable, eventually you piss everyone off.

1) The benefits of building on one chain:

Ecosystem Development teams LOVE native projects and, in many cases, do a fantastic end to end job helping applications go to market. From fundraising, to marketing, to product feedback, and beyond. In particular: Monad, Berachain, and Movement have done a fantastic job on this front. 
 
Monad has run some of the coolest events such as Monad Madness and The Foundry, and it is an awesome experience to have such a diehard community behind you, providing support. Berachain is fantastic about product feedback and have constantly focused on providing back to the applications building on their chain through programs like RFA, and Proof of Liquidity itself. Movement has helped ecosystem applications raise more capital in aggregate than they themselves have raised, and have supported builders through Battle of Olympus.
2) The difficulty of multichain:

Everyone loves the narrative of chain abstraction: Unifying liquidity, users, and reducing the barrier for onboarding new users outside crypto. The reality is that users generally have a "favorite chain" and there is very little you can do to get them to move. 
 
For builders, having an application that communicates or manages data across multiple blockchains creates issues around data staleness (what happens if your message takes too long to deliver and the data is no longer relevant?), block reorganization (Do you recreate double spend opportunities if one chain reorganizes during your operations?), liquidity fragmentation (Applications tend to have to collect governance tokens on a chain to build liquidity on AMMs/other venues, what happens when you want liquidity elsewhere and can't use those tokens?). These of course are all problems we are trying to solve for, but remains to be seen how successful we will be.

3) Your addressable market is not as big as you think:
If you pull up Defillama and look at the TVL on incumbent chains and applications, you will see that liquidity moves very slowly, and in the late stages of a protocol‚Äôs life cycle, usage tends to bleed down, but never hits zero.
 
I call these "dead deposits", you might think that money may move from Compound v2 or Maker DAO if you create "better" opportunities or technology, but the reality is, a lot of that liquidity is never moving. It could be lost wallet keys, it could be people that are happy to forget those assets after borrowing as much as they can against them, or they could have simply forgotten they have assets there.
 
So, in a lot of cases your opportunity for building a killer application and vacuum up all your competitors TVL is a lot smaller than it looks. The hot ball of fast-moving liquidity is noticeably smaller than total DeFi deposits, though I am quite confident we see continued DeFi growth this cycle as we have seen protocols like Aave hit ATH deposits (shout-out to the Aave team those guys are an incredible team).

4: The future looks bright:

While this post can be viewed as pessimistic in some ways, it is hard to describe how exciting it is to be building a crypto application right now with so many great destinations to consider. While I think long term, we see crosschain applications become the norm in the same way that a web2 application will build support for Windows, Mac, and Linux, right now picking the right ecosystem to build with and going all in on them is a great strategy.
 
I hope this writeup is useful to someone out there who is deep in thought of where to build or what community they would like to be a part of. The future of building in Crypto is bright with governments around the world starting to look at blockchain technology and mass onboarding events like we have seen with Solana recently.
 
If you have ever been looking for an excuse to start working on the project you have been thinking about, take this as that push. Come and build cool stuff with us, whether that be on any of the chains I mentioned above, or Ethereum, or L2s, or anywhere else.

Stay Floppy

name: rushi
text:
baby boomers are coming.

hats off to the @moonshot team for putting on a show yesterday - remember tweeting about these guys a while back and they've done nothing but execute phenomenal UX.

what's even more exciting is the rate of normies picking up crypto as an investment vehicle.

it will becoming increasingly clear that holding cash itself or putting money in the S&P 500 is a bad investment decision - inflation will kill you.

my thesis is that in the next 6 to 36 months baby boomers will pick up crypto at a disproportionate rate to other assets.

imagine the 60 year old farmer in oklahoma who has never believed in magic internet money but now is intrigued as their president launched a coin in the shores of the usa.

with this, there's a huge market for the Charles Schwab moment for crypto - a boomer-friendly crypto-native investment platform that offers various strategies with a gtm tailored towards retirement homes, local shops, rural farmers, local banks / family offices, etc.

imagine that same farmer put 5% of his or her capital into a "Memecoin Active Investment Fund". just based off yesterday, that farmer would have outperformed all of wall street in 12 hours.

i believe that this will begin the tradition for crypto to become a large holding if not a dominant holding for the fortune 500 and beyond. retail will be able to navigate cycles for btc and beyond effectively without getting burned while true defi avenues (think coinbase x morpho) will slowly be baked in.

the joke that crypto was to the entire world is slowly becoming a reality.

the rise of ai agents in daily life mixed with next-generation trading / investment products will displace tradfi in the 2030s and i could not be more excited.

traditional investment banking is doomed - keep your 10% returns.

name: rushi
text:
the space race for experimentation.

with the launches of many chains in Q1, the hunt for quality teams in high potential verticals will be the decision maker.

which chains have the most vibrant ai ecosystem?

which chains have the most loyal devs?

which chains have volume to attract fair launch projects?

we do a little of that yappin in this new ep.

specifically, for movement we've been ramping up for movuary.

some alpha:

- over the next few days, builders are going to start onboarding to the public mainnet as we gear up infra providers as well.

- a liquidity program to quite literally move capital into mansions ahead of launch

- a 0 to 1 ai accelerator to double down on our ai ecosystem

- mainnet

with one of the first mainnets of Q1, movement's sole mission by this time next year is to be the number one altvm.

lets ride.

name: rushi
text:
as we onboard builders to our mainnet launch, we're quickly realizing the power of move.

a year ago, we emphasized our edge being move-evm bringing the beauty of both move and evm in a unified environment.

today, the ecosystem and community has grown far beyond imagined - where we don't really need to support solidity.

evm builders who want to work with us are going thru full rewrites in move to build on movement while rustaceans are picking up move to catch up.

the folks who used evm on testnet are now realizing that not investing in move is an inherent weakness.

in fact, this was the thesis we pitched a year ago to investors - we would build a move-evm but the evm would slowly not be needed as move matures.

today, move is maturing and has soldified itself as the third major language with the potential to become 2.

few.

name: rushi
text:
why you should build in crypto:

got dinner with a close friend of mine whos pretty well regarded in the silicon valley scene.

he has no background in crypto and only really got into it because of me - honestly was a huge skeptic of the space.

his first idea revolved around building a consumer AI company - take on pinterest with AI.

despite having every venture fund reach out to him preempting him with term sheets, he declined that route.

some notes from that conversation:

- building in web2 consumer is quite literally impossible. the social graphs from Facebook, Instagram, Snapchat, etc are all extremely gated and the only way to access them is through paying exorbitant fees which pretty much cuts off all new consumer startups. its largely why we haven't seen any web2 social apps rival the early '10s incumbents.

- VCs often invest out of hope, not expectation. vcs hope that some incumbent will use AI to navigate the social graph discrepancy and build the next instagram - turns out even they agree, its not possible

- AI is largely overfunded and kingmade by the OpenAIs, Anthropics, Metas of the world. Largely hard for a scalable outcome now.

- the only thing interesting in the consumer / social space is crypto. AI x Social is already done (Meta AI agents, Twitter Grok integration etc). what's not done is the intersection of finance and social (the Diem Vision)

- crypto is still a wild west. big tech still hasn't come due to regulation (will change with new admin) and the winners have not been established (very few devs, little pmf, etc).

- for the first time, baby boomers voted for a pro-crypto president. there will be a major transfer in wealth towards digital assets as well an acknowledgement for decentralized asset ledgers.

the time to build in crypto is now. this is the early 2010s moment where infrastructure is ready (similar to after the early 2000s in web2), regulation is around the corner with a pro-crypto admin, and large institutional older-generation capital is about to be deployed.

important to note that this will not last forever. id say theres about half a decade left to innovate before the facebooks, instagrams, snapchats, nvidias, oracles, etc of the crypto landscape are established.

it is a quiet space race that will define the 2030s just like the space race in the 2010s for the internet defined the 2020s.

if you're thinking about tech, there is no other industry with as much potential as crypto.

do not be sidelined.

- the only thing interesting in the consumer / social space is crypto. AI x Social is already done (Meta AI agents, Twitter Grok integration etc). what's not done is the intersection of finance and social (the Diem Vision)

- crypto is still a wild west. big tech still hasn't come due to regulation (will change with new admin) and the winners have not been established (very few devs, little pmf, etc).

- for the first time, baby boomers voted for a pro-crypto president. there will be a major transfer in wealth towards digital assets as well an acknowledgement for decentralized asset ledgers.

the time to build in crypto is now. this is the early 2010s moment where infrastructure is ready (similar to after the early 2000s in web2), regulation is around the corner with a pro-crypto admin, and large institutional older-generation capital is about to be deployed.

important to note that this will not last forever. id say theres about half a decade left to innovate before the facebooks, instagrams, snapchats, nvidias, oracles, etc of the crypto landscape are established.

it is a quiet space race that will define the 2030s just like the space race in the 2010s for the internet defined the 2020s.

if you're thinking about tech, there is no other industry with as much potential as crypto.

do not be sidelined.

name: rushi
text:
this beautiful story has me thinking if this changes the game for donations

previously charitable donations were not necessarily scalable since it was purely dependent on human good will.

what if we start to see more ‚Äútokenized charities‚Äù or something along the lines where there are markets for different social goods.

yes its probably more volatile to manage but it could actually create a sustainable stream of capital for social movements instead of one off donations.

something like a gofundme + pumpfun would be interesting to see.

imagine a social movement gets to the point of WIF with hundreds of millions of dollars in liquidity used to drive good.

might change the game for social entrepreneurship / charity forever.

only possible with crypto.

quotedStatus.name: Siqi Chen
quotedStatus.text:
i am in tears. unbelievably grateful to the community that made this possible. thank you, thank you, thank you.

in addition to this $1M, we have also raised $250K in gofundme. yi and i are also donating another $100K from our personal funds on top to support the hankinson lab.

that comes out to a total of $1.35M in funding raised in the last 4 days that is going to make a real difference to the thousands of kids that are afflicted with this disease today. 

this is the single largest donation that has ever been made to Hankinson Lab.

i cannot tell you how much i love that our beautiful mira's name is associated with something beautiful like this in the world. 

while i still expect $MIRA to go to zero, and i strongly believe that nobody should buy a single token if they don't expect the same, if $MIRA ends up being something long lasting that can help direct even more funding to rare disease research, nothing would make me happier.

to that end, i have locked about 1/3 of what i still own in a one year lock. i have also paused the liquidation schedule, and per earlier commitment of advance notice, will instead begin liquidating at a much slower rate of 50,000 $MIRA per hour, starting in 24 hours, in order to maximize funding to rare disease research over the long run.

i am still figuring out next steps, but my commitment again is to continue have all funds across any token, any time, from the wallet associated with $MIRA to go 100% to supporting rare disease research (minus tax obligations).

i am also working to have 80% of all my remaining $MIRA tokens in a lock or multi-sig wallet controlled by people the community trusts.

more coming while i work on the above, but for now - thank you all, from the bottom of our hearts.

its for the people who believe in a movement.

and that is our edge.

quotedStatus.name: rushi
quotedStatus.text:
ecosystem pages today are so boring.

nobody wants to scroll through your list of 500+ partnerships.

admittedly, this is something we kinda have as well as it is considered to an extent (although we tend to showcase movement native teams).

crypto ecosystems need an app store - mobile first, broken down by categories, direct links to hot apps, and incentives to test out the apps.

we piloted this concept with parthenon and the reaction was amazing.

no more boring testnets with a dex, a bridge, and a few games.

a fully end-to-end MMO with built-in questing that rewards true users experimenting with apps.

the result was amazing: community members loved using our apps and were rewarded appropriately.

many have since asked for it back.

so we're bringing it back for mainnet.

parthenon V2 will be the first interface designed to be mobile-first and intuitive with a clear focus on the apps not the chain.

we'll have direct links to tiktok so creators (with @jokerace_io) can make short form content with their favorite movement apps and earn MOVE for bringing in users via platforms like @henrysocialxyz 

make blockchains usable and not boring.

parthenon V2 coming soon.

name: rushi
text:
crypto consumer apps have historically been unable to build away from mercenary "farm app for tokie" users.

think tiktok-first marketing changes this where every crypto consumer app will turn to tiktok for its userbase. pumpfun did a good job with this enabling normies to start streaming, trading, and using the app directly from tiktok.

the issue in the past is crypto apps never competed with web2 apps for marketing mindshare - crypto apps would market on CT while normie apps would market on instagram, tiktok, etc and cater to the youth.

if apps like @vybedotlol and @henrysocialxyz start doing guerrilla tiktok fitness influencer marketing, theres a real opportunity for the youth to start recognizing the edge crypto brings to daily ux - payments 10x faster, rewards 10x higher, and identity 10x more important.

the thesis for bottom up marketing starts and ends w tiktok.

if you're building a crypto consumer app and need help with tiktok gtm, dm me or @livingwithwill or @wiziswiz  we've set up a tiktok grants program to fund our ecosystem tiktok marketing endeavors.

need to talk to tiktok kols? need to hire short form content editors? 

we got you.

for free.

name: rushi
text:
what is movement's north star?

bringing back the libra vision.

the libra vision was cultivating an ecosystem of consumer-first applications running on crypto rails designed to outperform their non-crypto peers.

they did this by leveraging the facebook umbrella and establishing day 1 partnerships with the biggest companies in the world.

we all know the story - regulation sucked back then.

crypto was not ready for libra.

flash forward to today, we have a new regime that is crypto friendly, real breakthrough crypto apps that have outpaced their noncrypto comparisons (polymarket vs kalshi), and record high developer activities.

however, piecing back libra as it stood will prove to be difficult and honestly is not going to be movement's edge.

we're not going to win in the top down institutional battle today - players like Avalanche (cc @luigidemeo) and Solana are spending ample resources and have been evangelizing crypto to large institutions for nearly half a decade.

we're focused on on the bottoms up approach. my entire focus for the next 90 days will be attempting to touch as many scrappy teams in SF / NYC as possible.

teams that want to build the next uber, pinterest, snapchat, recognize market gaps, and use crypto to build a product that will compete with the major players listed below.

because to get spotify crypto pilled fully will take years.

but the moment you have a true spotify competitor built by a group of scrappy college kids and a preseed round that 10xs experiences for listeners and producers - spotify will be forced to listen.

in web2, uber faced a decade of regulatory hurdles. there was no way to convince taxi agencies to adopt rideshare.

uber forced them to adopt rideshare because they used a new technology (web2) to compete.

similarly, the main incumbent breakthrough we will observe is twofold:

- major institutions leaning into crypto (top down)
- small startups leveraging crypto to dethrone the big players

movement will be focused on the second tier almost exclusively with a high degree of focus towards the 19-24 yr old demographic.

hungry and scrappy builders fed up with lyft and spotify and looking to compete with crypto.

movement's contribution to the libra vision will be the homegrown crypto apps that force the big institutions to adopt crypto or go extinct.

others will focus on top down approach and thats also great!

we have 4 years to prove the libra vision (cc @santiagoroel) or die trying?

banger pod as usual with @theempirepod 

if you're looking to take on lyft, shopify, uber, paypal, etc - DM me and Santi.

lets ball.

name: rushi
text:
12 hours or so out from TGE.

honestly last few weeks has been brutal - 6am to 12pm nights, constant anxiety about launch, and hundreds of meetings with shareholders.

when we started movement two years ago, i never would have imagined this. 

we were two idiot kids in college with less than $500 in our bank account (picture below is from ethdenver 2 years ago after cooper sold his car to be able to afford engineer salaries).

we just really liked move lol.

and we wanted to see more people using it.

the name movement came from a wish of a democratic and builder-led movement for high-performance infrastructure.

we always knew that we wouldn't be the best technologists or the best researchers or the best financiers.

we just knew that we knew how to build a community and help builders succeed.

today, that's translated into over $45m in private venture funding for movement builders (more than the ecosystem), 60 live apps on testnet, 2100 olympians competing in our recent hackathon, and 52 regional active Movement groups.

and mans been a ride.

movement grew from two kids in a WW2 basement dorm to a team of 45+ of the baddest mfs ive met in my life.

tomorrow im sure will be hectic - prices up and down, airdrop shenanigans, mainnet beta raging.

and im sure ill get attacked or applauded depending on how it goes.

but regardless, im super proud to have built the movement to where it is today and more importantly that ive led atleast 20 other Rushi and Coopers to launch their own companys, raise, and hopefully be bigger than movement itself.

tomorrow is a beautiful day and excited for the world to see MOVE in action.

gmove to a new chapter in the Movement story.

name: rushi
text:
fud is bullish.

movement is a young team and brand. 

we‚Äôre unconventional, defiant, and borderline insane.

we‚Äôll make mistakes, learn, and improve in public.

oftentimes that means im on the chopping block and tbh it is mentally exhausting at times.

always keep your head up, realize tomorrow everyone forgets, and do your best to turn it into positivity.

almost always we turn every hate post into a meme that results in a new marketing campaign (i.e move mansions) and its probably not for everyone - but thats okay.

at the end of the day, if theres no fud or doubt about your mission, its probably not a mission worth chasing.

believe in something.

quotedStatus.name: David Marcus
quotedStatus.text:
How Libra Was Killed.

I never shared this publicly before, but since @pmarca opened the floodgates on @joerogan‚Äôs pod, it feels appropriate to shed more light on this.

As a reminder, Libra (then Diem) was an advanced, high-performance, payments-centric blockchain paired with a stablecoin that we built with my team at @Meta. It would‚Äôve solved global payments at scale. Prior to announcing the project, we spent months briefing key regulators in DC and abroad. We then announced the project in June 2019 alongside 28 companies. Two weeks later, I was called to testify in front of both the Senate Banking Committee and the House Financial Services Committee, which was the starting point of two years of nonstop work and changes to appease lawmakers and regulators.

By spring of 2021 (yes they slow played us at every step), we had addressed every last possible regulatory concern across financial crime, money laundering, consumer protection, reserve management, buffers, and so much more, and we were ready to launch.

We had worked on a slow rollout of a limited pilot that some members of the Fed‚Äôs Board of Governors were supportive of. At last, Chair Jay Powell was ready to let us move forward in a limited way. The story, as I heard it, is that Jay Powell was told by Treasury Secretary Janet Yellen at one of their biweekly meetings that allowing this project to move forward was ‚Äúpolitical suicide,‚Äù and she would not have his back if he let it happen. I wasn‚Äôt in the room when this conversation happened, so take these words with a grain of salt, but effectively this was the moment Libra was killed.

Shortly thereafter, the Fed organized calls with all the participating banks, and the Fed‚Äôs general counsel read a prepared statement to each of them, saying: ‚ÄúWe can‚Äôt stop you from moving forward and launching, but we are not comfortable with you doing so.‚Äù And just like that, it was over.

One essential point is worth making here. There was no legal or regulatory angle left for the government or regulators to kill the project. It was 100% a political kill‚Äîone that was executed through intimidation of captive banking institutions. That was the hardest part of this story for me personally. Not that we had failed, but that America, this country I immigrated to and became a proud citizen of because of its rule of law and value system, behaved in such a way for political reasons. It was a very tough pill to swallow.

The bright side of the story, though, was the many learnings from this wild ride. By the end of the project, we had made so many concessions to get a thumbs-up that the whole design of the network became a Frankenstein of our initial ambitions.

We also learned the biggest lesson of all, which is that if you‚Äôre trying to build an open money grid for the world‚Äîeventually moving trillions of dollars a day, designed to be here 100 years from now‚Äîyou have to build it on the most neutral, decentralized, unassailable network and asset, which, hands down, is Bitcoin.

And now this is what many of us who went through this scarring journey are building together at @Lightspark. And this time, we won‚Äôt stop until we get it done!

name: rushi
text:
the libra project was destined to change everything.

imagine the biggest social network taking on global banking and being able to send money from NYC to Bangkok at the speed of light natively on your mobile device.

with every major institution and enterprise partner lined up.

crypto was about to have its "aha" moment but was shut down due to regulation.

the move thesis still lived with the goal of reviving libra but in a web3 native way.

especially as regulation warms up under new legislation, we are getting closer to the original diem vision (https://t.co/ZGTPggJ05H)

gmove soon.

I wasn‚Äôt in the room when this conversation happened, so take these words with a grain of salt, but effectively this was the moment Libra was killed.

One essential point is worth making here. There was no legal or regulatory angle left for the government or regulators to kill the project. It was 100% a political kill‚Äîone that was executed through intimidation of captive banking institutions. That was the hardest part of this story for me personally. Not that we had failed, but that America, this country I immigrated to and became a proud citizen of because of its rule of law and value system, behaved in such a way for political reasons. It was a very tough pill to swallow.

The bright side of the story, though, was the many learnings from this wild ride. By the end of the project, we had made so many concessions to get a thumbs-up that the whole design of the network became a Frankenstein of our initial ambitions.

We also learned the biggest lesson of all, which is that if you‚Äôre trying to build an open money grid for the world‚Äîeventually moving trillions of dollars a day, designed to be here 100 years from now‚Äîyou have to build it on the most neutral, decentralized, unassailable network and asset, which, hands down, is Bitcoin.

And now this is what many of us who went through this scarring journey are building together at @Lightspark. And this time, we won‚Äôt stop until we get it done!

How Libra Was Killed.

I never shared this publicly before, but since @pmarca opened the floodgates on @joerogan‚Äôs pod, it feels appropriate to shed more light on this.

As a reminder, Libra (then Diem) was an advanced, high-performance, payments-centric blockchain paired with a stablecoin that we built with my team at @Meta. It would‚Äôve solved global payments at scale. Prior to announcing the project, we spent months briefing key regulators in DC and abroad. We then announced the project in June 2019 alongside 28 companies. Two weeks later, I was called to testify in front of both the Senate Banking Committee and the House Financial Services Committee, which was the starting point of two years of nonstop work and changes to appease lawmakers and regulators.

By spring of 2021 (yes they slow played us at every step), we had addressed every last possible regulatory concern across financial crime, money laundering, consumer protection, reserve management, buffers, and so much more, and we were ready to launch.

We had worked on a slow rollout of a limited pilot that some members of the Fed‚Äôs Board of Governors were supportive of. At last, Chair Jay Powell was ready to let us move forward in a limited way. The story, as I heard it, is that Jay Powell was told by Treasury Secretary Janet Yellen at one of their biweekly meetings that allowing this project to move forward was ‚Äúpolitical suicide,‚Äù and she would not have his back if he let it happen. I wasn‚Äôt in the room when this conversation happened, so take these words with a grain of salt, but effectively this was the moment Libra was killed.

Shortly thereafter, the Fed organized calls with all the participating banks, and the Fed‚Äôs general counsel read a prepared statement to each of them, saying: ‚ÄúWe can‚Äôt stop you from moving forward and launching, but we are not comfortable with you doing so.‚Äù And just like that, it was over.

One essential point is worth making here. There was no legal or regulatory angle left for the government or regulators to kill the project. It was 100% a political kill‚Äîone that was executed through intimidation of captive banking institutions. That was the hardest part of this story for me personally. Not that we had failed, but that America, this country I immigrated to and became a proud citizen of because of its rule of law and value system, behaved in such a way for political reasons. It was a very tough pill to swallow.

The bright side of the story, though, was the many learnings from this wild ride. By the end of the project, we had made so many concessions to get a thumbs-up that the whole design of the network became a Frankenstein of our initial ambitions.

We also learned the biggest lesson of all, which is that if you‚Äôre trying to build an open money grid for the world‚Äîeventually moving trillions of dollars a day, designed to be here 100 years from now‚Äîyou have to build it on the most neutral, decentralized, unassailable network and asset, which, hands down, is Bitcoin.

quotedStatus.text:
Name the buzzwords that EVM L2s created?

You came with "postconfirmations" (which are rebranded preconfirmations) after you got clowned on for referring to your construction as a "fast finality rollup". You can't even agree whether you're an optimistic rollup or a sidechain (the two constructions are mutually exclusive).

I called your bullshit on a panel and the best you could muster was "nobody uses them, so they can't be considered first" (???).

Your entire codebase is forked from Aptos with minor additions. Those "useless EVM L2s" created some of the fundamental building blocks that everybody uses (Polygon inventing Plonky2, Arbitrum building a Wasm-based general-purpose fraud proofs, etc.) while you struggled to add EVM support.

Get off your high horse.

name: rushi
text:
why ethereum ERC20?

try asking any custodian to support an altvm and its quite possibly the hardest thing to do atm - millions in cost up front, months in backlog (6-8 months), and a horrible UX for partners.

starknet was the first to pioneer this presumably because it was very difficult to support cairo. theres two contracts of STRK on ETH and Starknet itself - movement and presumably every altvm (believe fuel and eclipse are also down the same vein) will have to do this atleast today while custodian support is rather nascent.

just have one conversation with custodians and you‚Äôll see - getting QC is near impossible.

there is often a lot of operational burden that is behind the scenes that goes unnoticed.

name: rushi
text:
coop and i started movement as two move community members in college.

today, the Movement Network Foundation¬†reveals MOVE as the first step to mainnet launch with the community in mind.

historically, L2s have screwed YOU over.

they've farmed you for TVL, had years of farming, and then turned around and laid out predatory tokenomics designed for insiders.

not movement.

- insiders (team and investors) cannot and will not be able to stake at launch. 

- no predatory points programs that give all the value to whales while leaving you in the dust.

- 22% initial circulating with 10% for initial claims.

- MOVE deposits enabled at launch to bootstrap security for postconfirmations. you can directly contribute to the eventual security of the mainnet launch via your ownership. power to the people. 

movement's definitely been hell of a rollercoaster ride but every single internal call has been constructed with the community in mind.

we're super stoked for mainnet launch and always open to public feedback - feel free to dm any of us with ideas.

movement is a chain for the community, build by the community, for the community.

gmove.

name: rushi
text:
fundraising is just as big of a responsibility as it is a blessing.

its definitely cool to partner with leading minds in the space but its equally an added pressure to execute as the economics for a successful venture outcome progressively get more difficult.

treat each venture dollar as a personal dollar - you put your name on the line to grow your company. 

dont spend it on stupid shit, be the lowest paid on your team, and avoid complacency like the plague.

the absolute worst thing you can do is nothing - your investors are better off buying BTC then.
